# Guardrails Relationships

> Adapted from [Augmented Coding Patterns](https://github.com/lexler/augmented-coding-patterns/blob/main/documents/relationships.mmd).
> This graph shows how guardrails (patterns, skills, tests) relate to traps (anti-patterns, obstacles).

```mermaid
graph LR

  %% === OBSTACLES (inherent limitations — cannot eliminate, only compensate) ===
  subgraph Obstacles
    O1[Context Rot]
  end

  %% === TRAPS / ANTI-PATTERNS (what we protect against) ===
  subgraph Traps
    T1[Silent Breakdown]
    T2[Context Blindness]
    T3[Stale Stack]
    T4[Vibe Refactoring]
    T5[False Safety]
    T6[Agent Circles]
    T7[P50 vs Max]
    T8[Log Leak]
  end

  %% === GUARDRAILS (how we protect) ===
  subgraph Patterns
    P1[Attribute-driven Inventory]
    P2[Source-level Anti-pattern Gates]
    P3[Bug-as-Fixture]
    P4[Decision Guards]
    P5[Serialization Contract Tests]
    P6[Hierarchical Agent Instructions]
    P7[Concurrency with Real DB]
    P8[Attribute-driven PII Redaction]
    P9[Shared Cache Contract Tests]
  end

  subgraph Skills
    S1[Code Review Agent]
    S2[Security Audit]
    S3[DBA Audit]
    S4[Performance Audit]
    S5[API Design Audit]
    S9[Bot Audit]
    S6[Task Compliance]
    S7[i18n Audit]
    S8[Version Audit]
  end

